    <h2 style="margin-top:0">The most important caveat on this site</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      <strong>Nobody knows the expiration dates for certain — including us.</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      The National Housing Preservation Database estimates a LIHTC expiration by taking the year a
      property was placed in service and <strong>adding thirty</strong>. That is an assumption, not
      a filed date. It is the best available public estimate, and it is what powers our registry.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">It will be wrong in both directions:</p>
    <ul style="margin-top:14px;padding-left:22px">
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:8px;color:#243247"><strong>Too early</strong>, where a state required a longer affordability term than the federal minimum.</li>
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:8px;color:#243247"><strong>Too late</strong>, where an owner exited early through the qualified contract loophole — which federal law permits after just fifteen years.</li>
      <li style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:8px;color:#243247"><strong>Simply unknown</strong>, for the properties the NHPD flags as <em>inconclusive</em>, where the end date cannot be determined at all.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="pull red">
      That uncertainty is not a flaw in our data.
      <span style="display:block;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;margin-top:12px;opacity:.92">
        It is the finding. A federal preservation database is forced to <em>guess</em> at a date
        that ought to be a matter of public record — and in my own building, two law firms
        disagreed on it and it was settled by negotiation.
      </span>
    </div>

    <p class="lead">
      So: treat every date on this site as a <strong>starting point for a conversation with your
      housing agency</strong>, never as a legal fact. If your date matters, confirm it in writing
      with New York State Homes and Community Renewal.
    </p>

    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">How we choose sources</h2>
    <p class="lead"><strong>We lead with tenant-side research.</strong> The National Low Income Housing Coalition and PAHRC (who maintain the NHPD), Community Service Society, the National Housing Law Project, ANHD, TakeRoot Justice, Shelterforce.</p>
    <p class="lead"><strong>We use industry- and government-adjacent sources carefully</strong> — the Furman Center, Freddie Mac, HUD, the Federal Reserve. Their <em>filings</em> are solid: dates, addresses, unit counts, placed-in-service years. Their <em>framing</em> is not neutral, and we don't adopt it. We take the data and make our own argument.</p>
    <p class="lead"><strong>We name the source in the sentence</strong>, not in a footnote, so you can weigh it yourself.</p>
    <p class="lead"><strong>Disclosure:</strong> TakeRoot Justice represents the tenants of 63 Tiffany Place, including the author of this site.</p>

