    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">On the qualified contract loophole in New York</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      Federal law lets an owner exit LIHTC after fifteen years, not thirty, through the
      <strong>qualified contract</strong> process. Whether that applies to a given New York building
      is genuinely complicated, and we want to be precise about it.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      New York's allocation plans now <strong>require</strong> owners to waive the qualified
      contract right as a condition of receiving credits — New York City's QAP states that the owner
      "agrees to maintain the Extended Use period by including in the regulatory agreement a waiver
      of the right to seek a qualified contract." The state's DHCR plan was revised in 2008 to
      extend the minimum affordability period to thirty years.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      <strong>But those requirements came in later than many buildings.</strong> HCR's own guidance
      tells owners that they "may have waived the right to request a QC" and that they should
      "review their Regulatory Agreements and other documentation to determine their particular
      rights." The U.S. Treasury notes that properties financed before agencies adopted these
      policies "are still able to go through the qualified contract process."
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      So: a building financed in the 1990s may still hold that right, and a tenant cannot know
      without asking. Our calculator says <em>may</em>, never <em>will</em>, and tells you to ask HCR
      in writing. We will not guess at this on anyone's behalf.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      One thing worth knowing regardless: if a qualified contract does end the affordability period
      early, federal law still requires the owner — for <strong>three more years</strong> — to honour
      the maximum tax-credit rent for existing tenants <em>and to notify them that it happened</em>.
      Tenants in Missouri are currently suing owners who allegedly failed to do so.
    </p>
    <p class="lead" style="font-size:15px;color:var(--slate)">
      Sources: NYC HPD Qualified Allocation Plan; NYS HCR, <em>Qualified Contract Process Overview</em>;
      U.S. Department of the Treasury; Shelterforce.
    </p>

    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">Numbers we handle with care</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      <strong>The "90% of affordable housing" figure.</strong> The <em>New York Times</em> estimated
      in 2012 that LIHTC had built roughly 90% of the nation's affordable housing, and practitioners
      tell Shelterforce that 85–90% matches their experience. But Shelterforce is candid that
      <em>no definitive calculation exists</em> — there's no agreement on what counts as an
      "affordable" project. The defensible number is <strong>51%</strong> (NHPD): the share of
      existing federally subsidised homes that received LIHTC. We cite both, and say which is which.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      <strong>Freddie Mac's finding that most units stay affordable after exit.</strong> True on
      average, and we don't hide it. But their own caveat is that severe rent hikes remain likely for
      deeply-targeted units, their sample was 134 properties across seven metros, and they were
      unable to establish a clear statistical relationship between local market conditions and exit.
      That is not evidence that hot markets don't drive conversions — it's an admission that their
      data couldn't tell.
    </p>

    <h2 style="margin-top:52px">For reporters</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      Everything here is free to quote, free to reproduce, and free to argue with. No permission
      needed. If you want the underlying data, ask and I'll send it.
    </p>

    <div class="box" style="background:#fff;border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:20px;padding:26px 28px;margin-top:20px">
      <h3 style="color:var(--navy);font-size:19px">The story in four sentences</h3>
      <p style="margin-top:12px;font-size:17px;line-height:1.8;color:#243247">
        The Low-Income Housing Tax Credit is the country's main affordable housing programme, and it
        was never designed to be one — it's a tax instrument that produces housing as a byproduct.
        Its affordability runs thirty years and then simply stops, with no remedy written into the
        statute and, frequently, no reliable record of what the expiration date even is. Roughly
        845,000 homes are scheduled to lose their protections between 2024 and 2035. This has
        already happened to my building.
      </p>
    </div>

